Data Application Lab - Capstone Project #1: FinTech¶

Depei Zhang

07/26/2020

1. Introduction¶

1.1 Background¶

LendingClub [1] is an American peer-to-peer lending company, headquartered in San Francisco, California. It was the first peer-to-peer lender to register its offerings as securities with the Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC), and to offer loan trading on a secondary market. LendingClub is the world's largest peer-to-peer lending platform. The company claims that $15.98 billion in loans had been originated through its platform up to December 31, 2015. [2]

[1] https://www.lendingclub.com/

[2] https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LendingClub

1.2 Task & Purpose¶

The task of this project is to design an algorithm to select potentially high-return loans listed in lending club. To be specific, we will analyze the LendingClub's historical loan data, and use a machine learning model to predict whether or not one newly listed loan will be default in the future.

1.3 Metric & Evaluation¶

The 36-month term loan data from 2016Q1 to 2017Q2 will be used in this project, in which the loan data from 2016Q1 to 2017Q1 and the 2017Q2 data will be used as the training set and test set, respectively. The loan data will be trained based on some binary regression model, with the AUC, the area under the ROC curve, as the evaluation metric.

quarter_list = ['2016Q1', '2016Q2', '2016Q3', '2016Q4', '2017Q1', '2017Q2']

2.2 Feature Name Format Conversion¶

The feature names in the current & historical data are different, so we need to do some format conversion and extract the common features for the further analysis.

In [4]:
# get feature names for the current data, and convert to lower case
col_curr = list(df_curr.columns.values)
col_curr = [col.lower() for col in col_curr]

# get feature names for the historical data, and remove the underscore symbol
col_hist = list(df_hist.columns.values)
col_hist = [col.replace('_', '') for col in col_hist]

# extract the common & unique features
col_comm = list(set(col_curr) & set(col_hist))
col_curr_uni = list(set(col_curr) - set(col_hist))
col_hist_uni = list(set(col_hist) - set(col_curr))

# list the results
print(f"Common features: {len(col_comm)}\n{col_comm}\n")
print(f"df_curr unique features: {len(col_curr_uni)}\n{col_curr_uni}\n")
print(f"df_hist unique features: {len(col_hist_uni)}\n{col_hist_uni}\n")

# use two algorithms to compare the descriptions:
# 1. Longest Common Subsequence (LCS)
# 2. Longest Common Substring (LCSubStr)

# Dynamic Programming implementation of LCS problem
# https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/python-program-for-longest-common-subsequence/
def lcs(X, Y):
    # find the length of the strings
    m = len(X)
    n = len(Y)
    
    # declaring the array for storing the dp values
    L = [[None]*(n+1) for i in range(m+1)]
    
    """Following steps build L[m+1][n+1] in bottom up fashion 
    Note: L[i][j] contains length of LCS of X[0..i-1] 
    and Y[0..j-1]"""
    
    for i in range(m+1):
        for j in range(n+1):
            if i == 0 or j == 0:
                L[i][j] = 0
            elif X[i-1] == Y[j-1]:
                L[i][j] = L[i-1][j-1]+1
            else:
                L[i][j] = max(L[i-1][j] , L[i][j-1])
    
    # L[m][n] contains the length of LCS of X[0..n-1] & Y[0..m-1]
    return L[m][n]

# Finding Length of Longest Common Substring
# https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/longest-common-substring-dp-29/
# substring of X[0..m-1] and Y[0..n-1]
def LCSubStr(X, Y, m=-1, n=-1):
    if m == -1:
        m = len(X)
    if n == -1:
        n = len(Y)
    
    # Create a table to store lengths of
    # longest common suffixes of substrings.
    # Note that LCSuff[i][j] contains the
    # length of longest common suffix of
    # X[0...i-1] and Y[0...j-1]. The first
    # row and first column entries have no
    # logical meaning, they are used only
    # for simplicity of the program.
    
    # LCSuff is the table with zero
    # value initially in each cell
    LCSuff = [[0 for k in range(n+1)] for l in range(m+1)]
    
    # To store the length of
    # longest common substring
    result = 0
    
    # Following steps to build
    # LCSuff[m+1][n+1] in bottom up fashion
    for i in range(m + 1):
        for j in range(n + 1):
            if (i == 0 or j == 0):
                LCSuff[i][j] = 0
            elif (X[i-1] == Y[j-1]):
                LCSuff[i][j] = LCSuff[i-1][j-1] + 1
                result = max(result, LCSuff[i][j])
            else:
                LCSuff[i][j] = 0
    return result


# LCS score
col_lcs = [[lcs(col1, col2) / np.sqrt(len(col1) * len(col2)) for col2 in desc_hist_uni] for col1 in desc_curr_uni]
df_lcs = pd.DataFrame(np.array(col_lcs), index=col_curr_uni, columns=col_hist_uni)

# show heatmap
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 5))
plt.title('LCS')
sns.heatmap(df_lcs)
plt.show()

  • grade
  • subgrade
  • dti
  • verificationstatus = Verified
  • loanstatus = RENT
  • initialliststatus = f
  • delinq2yrs = 21.0

Features with strong negative influence on the charge off rate:

  • annualinc
  • tothicredlim
  • totalbclimit

# frequency encoding : zipcode, emptitle, addrstate
def frequency_encoder(df, col):
    dict_freq = df[col].value_counts().to_dict()
    return df[col].map(lambda x : dict_freq[x])

# zipcode
# use the first 3 numbers
df['zipcode'] = df['zipcode'].map(lambda x : str(x)[0:3] if x == x else '-999').astype(int)
df['zipcode_freq'] = frequency_encoder(df, 'zipcode')

# mark change
# keep the zipcode feature since it shows address info
cat_feature.remove('zipcode')
num_feature.append('zipcode')
num_feature.append('zipcode_freq')

# emptitle
df['emptitle'].fillna(value='nan', inplace=True)
df['emptitle_freq'] = frequency_encoder(df, 'emptitle')

# mark change
cat_feature.remove('emptitle')
num_feature.append('emptitle_freq')

# addrstate
df['addrstate'].fillna(value='NA', inplace=True)
df['addrstate_freq'] = frequency_encoder(df, 'addrstate')

# mark change
cat_feature.remove('addrstate')
num_feature.append('addrstate_freq')

# plot ROC curve
from sklearn.metrics import roc_curve, auc
def plot_roc_curve(model, X, y):
    assert(len(data) == len(y) and len(data) == 2)
    
    label = ['train', 'test']
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')
    
    for i in range(len(label)):
        y_prob = model.predict_proba(X[i])[:,1]
        fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y[i], y_prob)
        roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label='ROC curve - %s (AUC = %0.2f)' % (label[i], roc_auc))
    
    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('ROC Curve')
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.show()

plot_roc_curve(model_lr, [X_train, X_test], [y_train, y_test])

# plot ROC curve
def plot_roc_curve(model, data, y):
    assert(len(data) == len(y) and len(data) == 3)
    
    label = ['train', 'valid', 'test']
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
    plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], 'k--')
    
    for i in range(len(label)):
        y_prob = model.predict(data[i], ntree_limit=model.best_ntree_limit)
        fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y[i], y_prob)
        roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label='ROC curve - %s (AUC = %0.2f)' % (label[i], roc_auc))
    
    plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.ylim([0.0, 1.0])
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('ROC Curve')
    plt.legend(loc="lower right")
    plt.show()
    
plot_roc_curve(model_xgb, [data_train, data_valid, data_test], [y_train, y_valid, y_test])

3.4 Results¶

The test AUC score for Logistic Regression, Random Forest, XGBoost are 0.67, 0.69, 0.71, respectively.

  • XGBoost has the highest AUC score, benefited from the gradient boosting algorithm, however, the model interpretability of XGBoost is not so good. The extracted fscore can only qualitatively show the feature importance, which is much less accurate as the Logistic Regression coefficients.
  • Logistic Regression has the lowest AUC score due to its linearity, however, the fitted coefficients can quantitatively show how the target changes as a function of all the features.
    • Lending Club's loan grade and subgrade; interest rate; number of trades opened in past 24 months, number of accounts opened in past 12 months and number of inquiries in past 6 months have strong positive influence on the charge off rate.
    • Income was not verified by LC has strong negative influence on the charge off rate. This is counterintuitive, maybe due to the fact that income was not verified, the other screening process may be more strict and the loan amount will be limited.
  • Random Forest has an intermediate AUC score, while its model interpretability is similar as XGBoost.

4. Summary¶

  • We use Logistic Regression, Random Forest and XGBoost to predict the charge off probability of the loan data in LendingClub, achieving a best AUC score of 0.71.
  • From both EDA and Logistic Regression, we find some features with strong predicting power: Lending Club's loan grade and subgrade; interest rate; number of trades opened in past 24 months, number of accounts opened in past 12 months and number of inquiries in past 6 months.
  • The model can be used to predict the default rate on newly listed loans in Lending Club, and an automated trading strategy can be build on it.
  • However, the automated LendingClub trading strategy may not be very profitable. The interest rate for the Grade A loan is 8.46 - 10.81%, which is lower than the long term annual term of S&P 500, which is more than 10% including the dividend yield. Therefore, in order to make more profit on the strategy, we need to pick the relatively low risk loans in Grade B, C & D, which will have higher interest rates.
